<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="123" name="Coordination Compounds">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Compounds in which metal atoms are bound to a number of anions or neutral molecules are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coordination compounds</option><option id="B">Double salts</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also known as Complex compounds.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Salts that lose their identity in solution are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coordination compounds</option><option id="B">Double salts</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Wait, Double salts exist only in solid state and dissociate into ions in water. Coordination compounds retain identity.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Carnallite (KCl.MgCl2.6H2O) is an example of a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Double salt</option><option id="B">Coordination compound</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dissociates completely into K+, Mg2+ and Cl- ions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Central metal atom/ion and ligands bound to it are enclosed in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coordination sphere (Square brackets)</option><option id="B">Coordination polyhedron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: [Co(NH3)6]3+.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Anion or neutral molecule donor that binds to central metal is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ligand</option><option id="B">Matrix</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acts as a Lewis base.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A ligand that can bind through two donor atoms simultaneously is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Didentate / Bidentate</option><option id="B">Unidentate</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Ethylenediamine (en).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>EDTA (Ethylenediaminetetraacetate) is a ____ ligand.</text>
            <option id="A">Hexadentate</option><option id="B">Tetradentate</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Binds through 2 Nitrogen and 4 Oxygen atoms.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of ligand donor atoms to which metal is directly bonded is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coordination number</option><option id="B">Oxidation number</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: CN of Pt in [PtCl6]2- is 6.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ligand that can coordinate through two different atoms but one at a time is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ambidentate</option><option id="B">Chelating</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: NO2- (bonds via N or O).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Chelate effect ____ the stability of coordination compounds.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ring formation is entropy favored.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Spatial arrangement of ligand atoms around central metal is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coordination polyhedron</option><option id="B">Coordination number</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Octahedral, Tetrahedral, etc.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Werner's theory: Primary valence of a metal atom is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ionizable (Equal to oxidation state)</option><option id="B">Non-ionizable</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Satisfied by anions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Werner's theory: Secondary valence of a metal atom is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Non-ionizable (Equal to coordination number)</option><option id="B">Ionizable</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Directional in space.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In IUPAC naming, ligand names precede the metal name? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard convention.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>If complex is an anion, metal name ends with suffix ____.</text>
            <option id="A">-ate</option><option id="B">-ite</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Ferrate, Cuprate.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation state of metal is written in ____ numerals in parentheses.</text>
            <option id="A">Roman</option><option id="B">Arabic</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: (II), (III).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Neutral ligands are named as the ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Molecules name (with exceptions like Ammine, Aqua)</option><option id="B">Anions</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exceptions: NH3 (ammine), H2O (aqua), CO (carbonyl).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Anionic ligands end in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">-o</option><option id="B">-ate</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Chlorido, Cyanido, Hidroxido.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>IUPAC name for K4[Fe(CN)6] is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Potassium hexacyanidoferrate(II)</option><option id="B">Potassium ferricyanide</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fe is in +2 state.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>IUPAC name for [Co(NH3)3(H2O)3]Cl3 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Triamminetriaquacobalt(III) chloride</option><option id="B">Cobalt ammine aqua chloride</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ligands in alphabetical order.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Isomers with same molecular formula but different arrangement of atoms are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Isomers</option><option id="B">Allotropes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Structural or Stereoisomers.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Geometrical and Optical isomers are types of ____ isomers.</text>
            <option id="A">Stereoisomers</option><option id="B">Structural</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Spatial arrangement differences.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>cis-trans isomerism is a type of ____ isomerism.</text>
            <option id="A">Geometrical</option><option id="B">Optical</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used in square planar and octahedral complexes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Isomers that are non-superimposable mirror images are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Optical isomers (Enantiomers)</option><option id="B">Geometrical</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Brings about rotation of plane polarized light.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Condition for optical isomerism is absence of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Plane / Center of symmetry (Chirality)</option><option id="B">Donor atoms</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Molecule must be asymmetric.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Structural isomerism arising from ambidentate ligands is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Linkage isomerism</option><option id="B">Ionization</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: [Co(NH3)5(NO2)]Cl2 vs [Co(NH3)5(ONO)]Cl2.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Isomerism due to exchange of ligands between coordination and ionization sphere is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ionization isomerism</option><option id="B">Hydrate</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: [Co(NH3)5(SO4)]Br vs [Co(NH3)5Br]SO4.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Solvate isomerism (specifically with water) is also called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrate isomerism</option><option id="B">Linkage</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exchange of water molecules.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Isomerism in compounds having both cationic and anionic complexes is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Coordination isomerism</option><option id="B">Linkage</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Exchange of ligands between the two spheres.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Valence Bond Theory (VBT) explains bonding using ____ of orbitals.</text>
            <option id="A">Hybridization</option><option id="B">Overlap only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mixing of ns, np, nd orbitals.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Six-coordinated complexes with sp3d2 hybridization are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Outer orbital complexes</option><option id="B">Inner orbital</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High spin complexes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Six-coordinated complexes with d2sp3 hybridization are called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Inner orbital complexes</option><option id="B">Outer orbital</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Low spin complexes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hybridization for tetrahedral geometry is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">sp3</option><option id="B">dsp2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: [NiCl4]2-.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hybridization for square planar geometry is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">dsp2</option><option id="B">sp3</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: [Ni(CN)4]2-.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Crystal Field Theory (CFT) treats ligands as ____ points.</text>
            <option id="A">Negative point charges / Dipoles</option><option id="B">Spheres</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrostatic approach.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In octahedral field, d-orbitals split into t2g and ____ sets.</text>
            <option id="A">eg</option><option id="B">s</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Degeneracy is lifted.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Energy difference between split d-orbitals is called ____ energy.</text>
            <option id="A">Crystal Field Splitting Energy (CFSE / Δo)</option><option id="B">Ionization</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Depends on metal and ligand nature.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Series of ligands arranged in increasing order of field strength is ____ series.</text>
            <option id="A">Spectrochemical</option><option id="B">Periodic</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>I- < Br- < ... < CN- < CO.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ligands that cause large splitting in d-orbitals are ____ ligands.</text>
            <option id="A">Strong field</option><option id="B">Weak field</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Usually result in low spin complexes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Chlorophyll is a coordination compound of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Magnesium (Mg)</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Central metal in green plants.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hemoglobin is a coordination compound of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Iron (Fe)</option><option id="B">Copper</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Oxygen carrier in blood.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is an inner orbital complex?</text>
            <option id="A">[Co(NH3)6]3+</option><option id="B">[CoF6]3-</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>NH3 is strong field ligand, pairs up d-electrons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is an outer orbital complex?</text>
            <option id="A">[CoF6]3-</option><option id="B">[Co(NH3)6]3+</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>F- is weak field ligand.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Vitamin B12 is a coordination compound of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cobalt (Co)</option><option id="B">Nickel</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also known as cyanocobalamin.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Synergic bonding (bonding + back-bonding) is seen in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Metal carbonyls</option><option id="B">Metal hydrates</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strengthens the M-C bond and weakens C-O bond.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of geometrical isomers for [Pt(NH3)2Cl2]? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">2 (cis and trans)</option><option id="B">3</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Square planar MA2B2 type.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of geometrical isomers for [Pt(NH3)(Py)(Cl)(Br)]? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Square planar MABCD type.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>facial (fac) and meridional (mer) isomerism occurs in ____ complexes.</text>
            <option id="A">Octahedral MA3B3 type</option><option id="B">Square planar</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: [Co(NH3)3(NO2)3].</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Stability of complex is expressed by ____ constant (K).</text>
            <option id="A">Stability / Formation</option><option id="B">Ionization</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Higher K means more stable complex.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Overall stability constant βn is the ____ of stepwise constants.</text>
            <option id="A">Product</option><option id="B">Sum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>βn = K1 * K2 * ... * Kn.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coordination polyhedra: Pentagonal bipyramidal means Coordination Number is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">7</option><option id="B">6</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Higher coordination numbers are less common.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hybridization of Ni in [Ni(CO)4] is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">sp3 (Tetrahedral)</option><option id="B">dsp2 (Square planar)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>CO is strong field, Ni is in 0 state (d10 after pairing).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hybridization of Ni in [Ni(CN)4]2- is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">dsp2 (Square planar)</option><option id="B">sp3</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ni2+ is d8, CN- pairs them leaving one d empty.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic moment of [Fe(CN)6]3- is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1.73 BM (low spin d5)</option><option id="B">5.92 BM</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>One unpaired electron after pairing.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Magnetic moment of [Fe(H2O)6]3+ is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">5.92 BM (high spin d5)</option><option id="B">1.73 BM</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>5 unpaired electrons (water is weak field).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Splitting in tetrahedral field Δt is approx ____ times Δo.</text>
            <option id="A">4/9</option><option id="B">9/4</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Always smaller than octahedral splitting.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Color of [Ti(H2O)6]3+ is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Violet / Purple</option><option id="B">Colorless</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to absorption in yellow-green region (d-d transition).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>If light absorbed is Blue, the complex appears ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Orange / Yellow</option><option id="B">Blue</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complementary color principle.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The complex [Pt(en)2Cl2] can show ____ isomerism.</text>
            <option id="A">Geometrical and Optical</option><option id="B">Only Geometrical</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>cis-form is optically active.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is used as an anti-tumor drug?</text>
            <option id="A">cis-platin [Pt(NH3)2Cl2]</option><option id="B">EDTA</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Crucial medical application.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hard water hardness is estimated using ____ titration.</text>
            <option id="A">EDTA (Complexometric)</option><option id="B">Acid-Base</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forms complexes with Ca2+ and Mg2+.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Wilkinson's catalyst [P(Ph3)3RhCl] is used for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrogenation of alkenes</option><option id="B">Oxidation</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Homogeneous catalysis.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>In purification of Nickel (Mond's process), intermediate is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">[Ni(CO)4]</option><option id="B">[NiCl2]</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Volatile carbonyl.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Extraction of Silver and Gold uses ____ complexes.</text>
            <option id="A">Cyanido complexes</option><option id="B">Aqua complexes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Soluble dicyano species.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Ligand which donates through Carbon atom? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">CO / CN-</option><option id="B">NH3</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Leads to very stable complexes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxidation state of Fe in [Fe(CO)5] is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0</option><option id="B">+2</option><option id="C">+3</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Neutral carbonyl complex.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of d-electrons in Fe2+ is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6</option><option id="B">5</option><option id="C">4</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ar 3d6 config.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A complex with Δo > P (Pairing energy) will be ____ spin.</text>
            <option id="A">Low</option><option id="B">High</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrons prefer to pair up in lower orbitals.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A complex with Δo < P (Pairing energy) will be ____ spin.</text>
            <option id="A">High</option><option id="B">Low</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrons occupy higher energy orbitals to avoid pairing.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Effective Atomic Number (EAN) rule was given by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sidgwick</option><option id="B">Werner</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on noble gas config stability.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Isomerism shown by [Co(en)3]Cl3 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Optical</option><option id="B">Geometrical</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No geometrical isomers (facial etc only for MA3B3).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Bonding in metal carbonyls involves donation of lone pair from C to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Empty orbital of metal</option><option id="B">Filled orbital</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formation of Sigma bond.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Back-donation in metal carbonyls involves donation from filled metal d-orbitals to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Empty pi* orbital of CO</option><option id="B">Empty sigma</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formation of Pi bond.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Complex [Co(NH3)5Cl]Cl2 gives precipitate of ____ with AgNO3.</text>
            <option id="A">2 moles of AgCl</option><option id="B">3 moles</option><option id="C">1 mole</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Two Chloride ions are outside the sphere.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Geometry for dsp2 hybridization is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Square planar</option><option id="B">Tetrahedral</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common for d8 ions with strong ligands.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coordination number of Fe in [Fe(C2O4)3]3- is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">6</option><option id="B">3</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
